bib.title: Mechanism Of The Si(D,P) Reactions Below 3 Mev.

free_txt: H.V.E.C. 3 MeV Van de Graaff accelerator.
Two silicon surface barrier particle detectors
(the rotating detectors were ORTEC model SBFJ,
0.25 cm2 in active area with a 500 mu depletion depth)
were mounted to rotate about the target at radial
distances of 6.2 and 16.2 cm. The angular position of
these detectors is controlled and monitored remotely to
within +-3/4 degr. For use primarily in measuring the
excitation functions, an additional detector (the fixed
detector was an RCA model C-4, 0.2 cm2 active area with
a 450 mu depletion depth) was mounted at the 135 degr.
port hole on a sliding arm that allowed the detector to
be positioned anywhere from 1 to 25 cm from the target.
Gold or tantalum foils of thickness sufficient to stop
the elastically scattered deuterons were mounted in
front of the detectors.
The error in the scale of the cross sections,
a root-square value derived from uncertainties in the
target thickness, charge collection, solid angle
measurements, and counting statistics, were taken into
account. The extent to which oxygen, visible in the
experimental spectra, contributed to the weight of the
sample, is an unknown quantity, introducing a maximum
possible correction of less than 10%.
Data digitizing error
H.V.E.C. 3 MeV Van de Graaff accelerator.
The beam was collimated to an area of approximately
0.04 cm2 and limited to a maximum current of 1 mu-A.
Natural silicon or silicon enriched (68% 30Si)
with 30Si was evaporated onto the backings.
Target backings were constructed of gold leaf
(190 mu-g/cm2) mounted over 1.3-cm apertures in
tantalum blanks. The thickest targets employed in the
experiment were less than 10 keV thick to 2 MeV
deuterons.

The thickness of the target was measured by
weighing the amount of silicon deposited on thin
aluminum strips which were placed in the evaporation
chamber so as to receive a coating of silicon equal to
that received by the target. The weighing procedure
gave results reproducible to +-1 mu-g/cm2. The error
assigned includes an estimate of the uncertainty in
the uniformity of the deposited layer.
